These bills protect what the late civil rights hero and Congressman John Lewis called ‚Äúone of the most important blessings of our democracy,‚Äù and I urge everyone to keep speaking up about the need to safeguard our fundamental right to vote.

I‚Äôm proud to lead the Freedom to Vote Act, which sets basic federal standards so all Americans can cast their ballots in the way that works best for them, and I strongly support the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act to repair and restore the Voting Rights Act.

Since 2020, states have passed over 50 restrictive voting laws. These laws aren‚Äôt empty threats‚Äîthey represent real efforts to stop people from voting. It‚Äôs time to pass legislation to safeguard our democracy for generations to come.

It is no coincidence that after the 2020 election ‚Äì when more Americans voted than ever before in what the Department of Homeland Security called ‚Äúthe most secure election in American history‚Äù  ‚Äì there was a flood of state election laws meant to suppress votes.
We need to set basic federal standards like those in the Freedom to Vote Act to ensure that Americans can participate in our democracy. When we fight for voting rights, we fight for our democracy.

From the removal of mail ballot drop boxes and long lines at polling places to limiting early voting and making it harder to register to vote, too many Americans have faced serious obstacles to voting, especially in communities that have been historically disenfranchised.
It is Congress‚Äôs responsibility to fully restore the Voting Rights Act and honor the legacy of those who fought to protect the right to vote.

The landmark Voting Rights Act of 1965 broke down barriers to the ballot box and was the result of the tireless work of people like the late Congressman John Lewis who put their lives on the line to guarantee voting rights for all.
